Parag Shetye wrote:

&gt;public void testCreateBatchLabelNoInnerClass() {
&gt;
&gt;   try {
&gt;      BatchLabel aBatchLabel = new BatchLabel(
&gt;         &quot;20010530&quot;,  &quot;A13&quot;,  &quot;1&quot; );
&gt;      assert ( aBatchLabel.getBatchLabel().equals(
&gt;         &quot;A13-1 EXP. 05/01&quot; ) ) ;
&gt;   } catch (Exception e) {
&gt;      assert ( &quot;Exception:&quot; + e, false );
&gt;   }
&gt;
&gt;   try {
&gt;      BatchLabel aBatchLabel = new BatchLabel(
&gt;         &quot;20010530&quot;,  &quot;A13&quot;,  &quot;&quot; );
&gt;      assert ( aBatchLabel.getBatchLabel().equals(
&gt;         &quot;A13 EXP. 05/01&quot; ) ) ;
&gt;   } catch (Exception e) {
&gt;      assert ( &quot;Exception:&quot; + e, false );
&gt;   }
&gt;

How about chaining these two constructors such that you can test one and 
feel confident the other won&#39;t break?

&gt;
&gt;   try {
&gt;      BatchLabel aBatchLabel = new BatchLabel(
&gt;         &quot;20011231&quot;,  &quot;A13&quot;,  &quot;1&quot; );
&gt;      assert ( aBatchLabel.getBatchLabel().equals(
&gt;         &quot;A13-1 EXP. 12/01&quot; ) ) ;
&gt;   } catch (Exception e) {
&gt;      assert ( &quot;Exception:&quot; + e, false );
&gt;   }
&gt;
&gt;   try {
&gt;      BatchLabel aBatchLabel = new BatchLabel(
&gt;         &quot;20010101&quot;,  &quot;A13&quot;,  &quot;1&quot; );
&gt;      assert ( aBatchLabel.getBatchLabel().equals(
&gt;         &quot;A13-1 EXP. 01/01&quot; ) ) ;
&gt;   } catch (Exception e) {
&gt;      assert ( &quot;Exception:&quot; + e, false );
&gt;   }
&gt;

Only the date changes here. Is it reasonable to expect that if the first 
test passes, the second will pass as well?

&gt;
&gt;   try {
&gt;      BatchLabel aBatchLabel = new BatchLabel(
&gt;         &quot;20010101&quot;,  &quot;A123&quot;, &quot;99&quot; );
&gt;      assert ( aBatchLabel.getBatchLabel().equals(
&gt;         &quot;A123-99 EXP. 01/01&quot; ) ) ;
&gt;   } catch (Exception e) {
&gt;      assert ( &quot;Exception:&quot; + e, false );
&gt;   }
&gt;
&gt;   try {
&gt;      BatchLabel aBatchLabel = new BatchLabel(
&gt;         &quot;2001530&quot;,   &quot;A999&quot;, &quot;&quot; );
&gt;   } catch (Exception e) {
&gt;      assert( &quot;Wrong Exception thrown: &quot; + e,
&gt;         e.getClass().equals(
&gt;         BadDateException.class )) ;
&gt;   }
&gt;

How is the first test here different than the first pair of tests above? 
I&#39;ll buy the exceptional test.

&gt;
&gt;   try {
&gt;      BatchLabel aBatchLabel = new BatchLabel(
&gt;         &quot;20010530&quot;,   &quot;913&quot;, &quot;1&quot; );
&gt;   } catch (Exception e) {
&gt;      assert( &quot;Wrong Exception thrown: &quot; + e,
&gt;         e.getClass().equals(
&gt;         BadLotException.class )) ;
&gt;   }
&gt;

OK, I take it there are different exceptions for each slot of 
BatchLabel. I personally don&#39;t throw exceptions from constructors, but 
nevertheless it&#39;s good to test exceptional conditions. How do I know lot 
#913 is bad?


The other approach is to drive the tests with data since that&#39;s the only 
thing changing in the tests you&#39;ve supplied.

Write a single test method that reads each line of this file, asserting 
the last column:

20010530, A13, 1, A13-1 EXP. 05/01
20010530, A13,  , A13 EXP. 05/01
20011231, A13, 1, A13-1 EXP. 12/01
20010101, A13, 1, A13-1 EXP. 01/01
20010530, 913, 1, BadDateException


&gt;
&gt;The second limitation is that JUnit will stop the testing after the
&gt;first failure--the remaining test cases won&#39;t be executed.
&gt;

I call that a feature for unit testing. If you want alternatives, check 
out the FAQ regarding multiple failures. I might be inclined to just log 
failures when I&#39;m running acceptance tests, though I&#39;ve yet to encounter 
a situation when failing immediately wasn&#39;t the desired effect.

&gt;
